## 5. Agentic AI: When the Loop Gains Autonomy

The failure modes described above become categorically more severe when predictive systems are granted agency — the capacity to take autonomous actions toward self-set or externally defined goals without continuous human review.

BCG's December 2025 analysis found that AI-related incidents **rose 21% in the preceding year** and that "autonomous agents pose new risks that are harder to manage given less human oversight and a lack of adequate behavioral monitoring." The Association for Computing Machinery's policy brief on systemic risks of agentic AI identified a taxonomy of risks directly applicable to the architectural failures discussed in this paper: loss of control, manipulation and deception, goal-seeking behavior, self-improvement, and recursive coordination without external checks.

AIGN Global's governance analysis identifies the most dangerous emergent property of multi-agent systems: **recursive validation loops**, in which agents validate each other's decisions without external checks, creating an internally consistent but externally uncorrected epistemic closure. This is precisely the failure mode that makes agentic AI in healthcare, finance, criminal adjudication, and infrastructure uniquely dangerous: the system can achieve high internal coherence — every agent agreeing with every other — while being systematically wrong.

The extreme endpoint of this trajectory is lethal autonomous weapons systems (LAWS). The International Committee of the Red Cross defines these as weapons that "can search for, detect, identify, select, and attack targets without meaningful human intervention." Human Rights Watch's April 2025 report found that such systems "would contravene the rights to life, peaceful assembly, privacy, and remedy as well as the principles of human dignity and non-discrimination." Over 120 countries have endorsed a new international treaty framework, and the UN Secretary-General has issued repeated calls for a global ban on fully autonomous targeting systems.

The governance gap common across all these domains is the same: **systems with increasing autonomy and real-world impact but decreasing human accountability**.

